post_text: Ryan School parents: We have been working diligently to come up with a plan to return to learning. We have worked hard to only give accurate information when we have it. We have a plan that we will release at the first of next week. We need to wait until then because there is a state board meeting on Thursday that could affect our plan. As soon as we can I will get something to you so that you can make informed decisions about the upcoming school year. I do apologize for how long it is taking. Please understand that every decision we make has the best interest of our students, their families, and our community in mind.

post_text: My name is Madisen Rhoades. I have attended Ryan Public Schools since the 7th grade. I have been a member of our FFA chapter since my 8th grade year. During my Sophomore year I held the FFA office of Historian, and Vice President my Junior and Senior year. I have been a member of the BETA club since my Sophomore year and now serving as the club President. As a Senior I am a member of the yearbook staff. During my time at Ryan, I have played Fast-Pitch and Slow-Pitch Softball since my 7th grade year. Also playing Basketball during my 7th, 8th, and Freshman years. I participated in Track in my 7th and Freshman years, along with Cross Country during 7th grade. I plan to continue attending college and earn a degree in Biological Health Sciences.

Ryan High School is proud to join the nation wide campaign to honor the 2020 Senior Class.

High schools around Oklahoma and across the country are banding together to honor the senior class of 2020 amidst the corona virus pandemic.

On Friday, April 10th, at 8:20 pm all fields at Bob Givens Sports Complex and all outdoor stadiums around the state and country will turn on their lights for 20 minutes to show their appreciation for the senior class, families, athletes and coaches as part of the ‚ÄúBe the Light‚Äù campaign.

The lights are a beacon to show the Ryan Senior Class we are thinking of them and to remind them there will be a time when we are all together again.

The ‚ÄúBe the Light‚Äù campaign has been spreading across the nation as schools look for a way to celebrate their graduating seniors who are having their final memories of high school stripped away from them because of the outbreak.

Go Cowboys!

As you probably already know The State Board of Education voted to close school buildings across Oklahoma. Schools are supposed to transition to "Distance Learning". Lets make sure everyone understands this does not mean everything will have to move to online! We have started having meetings to come up with a plan that fits our students and community the best. We will have more information about the Distance Learning next week.

We have also had lots of questions about numerous activities. Prom and graduation at the top of the list. Those are currently postponed as we wait and see what happens during these uncertain times. We will do our best to do everything we can for our students as soon as we are allowed to.

Thank you for your patience and support!!

Those students who attended where recognized for their high academics. Student who scored above the 85th percentile on a nationally normed test and maintained a 3.4 GPA, received a Standard I . Students maintaining a 4.00 GPA the preceding two semesters, received a Standard II. We are so proud of these students and their accomplishment.

post_text:
The JR Class sold 88 dozen rolls and cinnamon rolls before the Thanksgiving break. On Saturday the 23rd a group of five JR helpers, Mrs. Amy Morgan, and the class sponsors Mr. Miranda and Ms. Underwood, met in the school's kitchen and made the rolls. The five students were awesome workers. They jumped into every stage of the baking process and just excelled. The class wants to give a special thanks to Mrs. Lowry for helping obtain most of the supplies. We want to give a very special thank you to Mrs. Amy Morgan who taught us the recipe and stayed working with us from 7am until about 4pm. We could not have done it without her.

The JR Class will be having a bake sale Monday the 9th in the gym lobby during the basketball games. The bake sale will be on a donation basis. Please come and support the JR Class.

We are extremely excited to be starting our new after school program! We have received a Federal 21st Century Grant to fund this program.

The 21st Century Grant is a 5 year grant so we will be able to at least run the program for 5 years. We are happy to be offering this opportunity to our students and our community!!

The only thing we ask from parents is that we need you to send your children to the program. We will also offer summer school in the month of June!!!

Below is the enrollment form that will be going home with elementary students today!

post_text:
Update: the truck is not able to get here in time to fill up with water and then set up to pump at the school. We will have the truck available tomorrow at the school. We hope to have the truck set up and pumping by 9:00 am

The water truck is coming tonight. They will be here later than expected. Probably will be at least 10:00pm before it gets here. It will only be pumping water for about an hour. Then will resume pumping in the morning. I will update this post when I have a better idea of their arrival. Please comment if you know you will come get water tonight.

post_text: School will be in session tomorrow. We will start one hour late. Classes will start at 9:00am and breakfast will be served at 8:30am. Busses will run 45 minutes later than normal. We still do not have water. I have been in contact with the Health Inspector and the DEQ. We will be able to offer breakfast, lunch, and snack. We will have bathrooms that flush and water and soap to wash hands. Obviously we will be hauling water in on a pretty consistent basis throughout the day. We will have the safety and health of our students as the biggest priority while our town figures out this water issue. Thank you for you understanding in advance!
